<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1436,1301,1927]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,281,1301,1327]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
This is most slender and elongate subspecies and can be distinguished from other subspecies by its pronotum flat or very slightly selliform, not concave; integument smooth, yellowish-buff with fine bluish or purplish marking and speckling; antennae dark with distinct yellow rings, equal to or slightly longer than head and pronotum together.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1436,1301,1927]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,314,1461,1487]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Habitats:</emphasis>
The preferred food plant is 
<emphasis box="[652,883,1461,1486]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<taxonomicName box="[652,879,1461,1486]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Apocynaceae" genus="Calotropis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="procera">Calotropis procera</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
a common shrub throughout the Saharian belt which favours sandy soil and semi-arid conditions. The readiness to accept alternative food plants has enabled 
<emphasis box="[151,301,1541,1566]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Poekilocenis</emphasis>
to survive in some areas where 
<taxonomicName box="[702,826,1541,1566]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Apocynaceae" genus="Calotropis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[702,826,1541,1566]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Calotropis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is scarce or even absent. This is the most mobile member of the genus in which both sexes especially the females have proportionately longer wings.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
